__bs__ I will always remember the first time I met the girl in the blue uniform .
__bs__ I was eight at the time , living in the village with my grandmother , who was raising me and other children .
__bs__ Famine had hit my country of Zimbabwe , and we just didn &apos;t have enough to eat .
__bs__ We were hungry .
__bs__ And that &apos;s when the girl in the blue uniform came to my village with the United Nations to feed the children .
__bs__ As she handed me my porridge , I asked her why she was there , and without hesitation , she said , &quot; As Africans , we must uplift all the people of Africa . &quot;
__bs__ I had absolutely no idea what she meant .
__bs__ ( Laughter ) But her words stuck with me .
__bs__ Two years later , famine hit my country for the second time .
__bs__ My grandmother had no choice but to send me to the city to live with an aunt I had never met before .
__bs__ So at the age of 10 , I found myself in school for the very first time .
__bs__ And there , at the city school , I would experience what it was to be unequal .
__bs__ You see , in the village , we were all equal .
__bs__ But in the eyes and the minds of the other kids , I was not their equal .
__bs__ I couldn &apos;t speak English , and I was way behind in terms of reading and writing .
__bs__ But this feeling of inequality would get even more complex .
__bs__ Every school holiday spent back in the village with my grandmother made me consciously aware of the inequalities this incredible opportunity had created within my own family .
__bs__ Suddenly , I had much more than the rest of my village .
__bs__ And in their eyes , I was no longer their equal .
__bs__ I felt guilty .
__bs__ But I thought about the girl in the blue uniform , and I remember thinking , &quot; &quot; That &apos;s who I want to be — someone like her , someone who uplifts other people . &quot; &quot; This childhood experience led me to the United Nations , and to my current role with UN Women , where we are addressing one of the greatest inequalities that affects more than half of the world &apos;s population — women and girls .
__bs__ Today , I want to share with you a simple idea that seeks to uplift all of us together .
__bs__ Eight months ago , under the visionary leadership of Phumzile Mlambo-Ngcuka , head of UN Women , we launched a groundbreaking initiative called HeForShe , inviting men and boys from around the world to stand in solidarity with each other and with women , to create a shared vision for gender equality .
__bs__ This is an invitation for those who believe in equality for women and men , and those who don &apos;t yet know that they believe .
__bs__ The initiative is based on a simple idea : that what we share is much more powerful than what divides us .
__bs__ We all feel the same things .
__bs__ We all want the same things , even when those things sometimes remain unspoken .
__bs__ HeForShe is about uplifting all of us , women and men together .
__bs__ It &apos;s moving us towards an inflection point for gender equality .
__bs__ Imagine a blank page with one horizontal line splitting it in half .
__bs__ Now imagine that women are represented here , and men are represented here .
__bs__ In our current population , HeForShe is about moving the 3.2 billion men , one man at a time , across that line , so that ultimately , men can stand alongside women and be on the right side of history , making gender equality a reality in the 21st century .
__bs__ However , engaging men in the movement would prove quite controversial .
__bs__ Why invite men ? They are the problem .
__bs__ ( Laughter ) In fact , men don &apos;t care , we were told .
__bs__ But something incredible happened when we launched HeForShe .
__bs__ In just three days , more than 100,000 men had signed up and committed to be agents of change for equality .
__bs__ Within that first week , at least one man in every single country in the world stood up to be counted , and within that same week , HeForShe created more than 1.2 billion conversations on social media .
__bs__ And that &apos;s when the emails started pouring in , sometimes as many as a thousand a day .
__bs__ We heard from a man out of Zimbabwe , who , after hearing about HeForShe , created a &quot; &quot; husband school . &quot; &quot; ( Laughter ) He literally went around his village , hand-picking all of the men that were abusive to their partners , and committed to turn them into better husbands and fathers .
__bs__ In Pune , India , a youth advocate organized an innovative bicycle rally , mobilizing 700 cyclists to share the HeForShe messages within their own community .
__bs__ In another impact story , a man sent a very personal note of something that had happened in his own community .
__bs__ He wrote , &quot; &quot; Dear Madam , I have lived all of my life next door to a man who continuously beats up his wife .
__bs__ Two weeks ago , I was listening to my radio , and your voice came on , and you spoke about something called the HeForShe , and the need for men to play their role .
__bs__ Within a few hours , I heard the woman cry again next door , but for the first time , I didn &apos;t just sit there .
__bs__ I felt compelled to do something , so I went over and I confronted the husband .
__bs__ Madam , it has been two weeks , and the woman has not cried since .
__bs__ Thank you for giving me a voice . &quot; &quot; ( Applause ) Personal impact stories such as these show that we are tapping into something within men , but getting to a world where women and men are equal is not just a matter of bringing men to the cause .
__bs__ We want concrete , systematic , structural change that can equalize the political , economic and social realities for women and men .
__bs__ We are asking men to make concrete actions , calling them to intervene at a personal level , to change their behavior .
__bs__ We are calling upon governments , businesses , universities , to change their policies .
__bs__ We want male leaders to become role models and change agents within their own institutions .
__bs__ Already , a number of prominent men and leaders have stepped up and made some concrete HeForShe commitments .
__bs__ In a few early success stories , a leading French hospitality company , Accor , has committed to eliminate the pay gap for all of its 180,000 employees by 2020 .
__bs__ ( Applause ) The government of Sweden , under its current feminist government , has committed to close both the employment and the pay gap for all of its citizens within the current electoral term .
__bs__ In Japan , the University of Nagoya is building , as part of their HeForShe commitments , what will become one of Japan &apos;s leading gender-research centers .
__bs__ Now , eight months later , a movement is building .
__bs__ We are seeing men sign up from every single walk of life , and from every single corner in the world , from the United Nations &apos; own Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon to the Secretary-Generals of NATO and the EU Council , from the prime minister of Bhutan to the president of Sierra Leone .
__bs__ In Europe alone , all the male EU Commissioners and the members of Parliament of the Swedish and Iceland governments have signed up to be HeForShe .
