__bs__ In the brain , that is especially critical ; its intense electrical activity uses up a quarter of the body &apos;s entire energy supply , even though the brain accounts for only about two percent of the body &apos;s mass .
__bs__ So the circulatory system solves the nutrient delivery problem by sending blood vessels to supply nutrients and oxygen to every corner of our body .
__bs__ You can actually see it in this video here .
__bs__ Here , we &apos;re imaging blood vessels in the brain of a living mouse .
__bs__ The blood vessels form a complex network that fills the entire brain volume .
__bs__ They start at the surface of the brain , and then they dive down into the tissue itself , and as they spread out , they supply nutrients and oxygen to each and every cell in the brain .
__bs__ Now , just as every cell requires nutrients to fuel it , every cell also produces waste as a byproduct , and the clearance of that waste is the second basic problem that each organ has to solve .
__bs__ This diagram shows the body &apos;s lymphatic system , which has evolved to meet this need .
__bs__ It &apos;s a second parallel network of vessels that extends throughout the body .
__bs__ It takes up proteins and other waste from the spaces between the cells , it collects them , and then dumps them into the blood so they can be disposed of .
__bs__ But if you look really closely at this diagram , you &apos;ll see something that doesn &apos;t make a lot of sense .
__bs__ So if we were to zoom into this guy &apos;s head , one of the things that you would see there is that there are no lymphatic vessels in the brain .
__bs__ But that doesn &apos;t make a lot of sense , does it ?
__bs__ I mean , the brain is this intensely active organ that produces a correspondingly large amount of waste that must be efficiently cleared .
__bs__ And yet , it lacks lymphatic vessels , which means that the approach that the rest of the body takes to clearing away its waste won &apos;t work in the brain .
__bs__ So how , then , does the brain solve its waste clearance problem ?
__bs__ Well , that seemingly mundane question is where our group first jumped into this story , and what we found as we dove down into the brain , down among the neurons and the blood vessels , was that the brain &apos;s solution to the problem of waste clearance , it was really unexpected .
__bs__ It was ingenious , but it was also beautiful .
__bs__ Let me tell you about what we found .
__bs__ So the brain has this large pool of clean , clear fluid called cerebrospinal fluid .
__bs__ We call it the CSF .
__bs__ The CSF fills the space that surrounds the brain , and wastes from inside the brain make their way out to the CSF , which gets dumped , along with the waste , into the blood .
__bs__ So in that way , it sounds a lot like the lymphatic system , doesn &apos;t it ?
__bs__ But what &apos;s interesting is that the fluid and the waste from inside the brain , they don &apos;t just percolate their way randomly out to these pools of CSF .
__bs__ Instead , there is a specialized network of plumbing that organizes and facilitates this process .
__bs__ You can see that in these videos .
__bs__ Here , we &apos;re again imaging into the brain of living mice .
__bs__ The frame on your left shows what &apos;s happening at the brain &apos;s surface , and the frame on your right shows what &apos;s happening down below the surface of the brain within the tissue itself .
__bs__ We &apos;ve labeled the blood vessels in red , and the CSF that &apos;s surrounding the brain will be in green .
__bs__ Now , what was surprising to us was that the fluid on the outside of the brain , it didn &apos;t stay on the outside .
__bs__ Instead , the CSF was pumped back into and through the brain along the outsides of the blood vessels , and as it flushed down into the brain along the outsides of these vessels , it was actually helping to clear away , to clean the waste from the spaces between the brain &apos;s cells .
__bs__ If you think about it , using the outsides of these blood vessels like this is a really clever design solution , because the brain is enclosed in a rigid skull and it &apos;s packed full of cells , so there is no extra space inside it for a whole second set of vessels like the lymphatic system .
__bs__ And what &apos;s amazing is that no other organ takes quite this approach to clearing away the waste from between its cells .
__bs__ This is a solution that is entirely unique to the brain .
__bs__ But our most surprising finding was that all of this , everything I just told you about , with all this fluid rushing through the brain , it &apos;s only happening in the sleeping brain .
