__bs__ There &apos;s nothing wrong with you .
__bs__ What you are is a multipotentialite .
__bs__ ( Laughter ) ( Applause ) A multipotentialite is someone with many interests and creative pursuits .
__bs__ It &apos;s a mouthful to say .
__bs__ It might help if you break it up into three parts : multi , potential , and ite .
__bs__ You can also use one of the other terms that connote the same idea , such as polymath , the Renaissance person .
__bs__ Actually , during the Renaissance period , it was considered the ideal to be well-versed in multiple disciplines .
__bs__ Barbara Sher refers to us as &quot; &quot; scanners . &quot; &quot; Use whichever term you like , or invent your own .
__bs__ I have to say I find it sort of fitting that as a community , we cannot agree on a single identity .
__bs__ ( Laughter ) It &apos;s easy to see your multipotentiality as a limitation or an affliction that you need to overcome .
__bs__ But what I &apos;ve learned through speaking with people and writing about these ideas on my website , is that there are some tremendous strengths to being this way .
__bs__ Here are three multipotentialite super powers .
__bs__ One : idea synthesis .
__bs__ That is , combining two or more fields and creating something new at the intersection .
__bs__ Sha Hwang and Rachel Binx drew from their shared interests in cartography , data visualization , travel , mathematics and design , when they founded Meshu .
__bs__ Meshu is a company that creates custom geographically-inspired jewelry .
__bs__ Sha and Rachel came up with this unique idea not despite , but because of their eclectic mix of skills and experiences .
__bs__ Innovation happens at the intersections .
__bs__ That &apos;s where the new ideas come from .
__bs__ And multipotentialites , with all of their backgrounds , are able to access a lot of these points of intersection .
__bs__ The second multipotentialite superpower is rapid learning .
__bs__ When multipotentialites become interested in something , we go hard .
__bs__ We observe everything we can get our hands on .
__bs__ We &apos;re also used to being beginners , because we &apos;ve been beginners so many times in the past , and this means that we &apos;re less afraid of trying new things and stepping out of our comfort zones .
__bs__ What &apos;s more , many skills are transferable across disciplines , and we bring everything we &apos;ve learned to every new area we pursue , so we &apos;re rarely starting from scratch .
__bs__ Nora Dunn is a full-time traveler and freelance writer .
__bs__ As a child concert pianist , she honed an incredible ability to develop muscle memory .
__bs__ Now , she &apos;s the fastest typist she knows .
__bs__ ( Laughter ) Before becoming a writer , Nora was a financial planner .
__bs__ She had to learn the finer mechanics of sales when she was starting her practice , and this skill now helps her write compelling pitches to editors .
__bs__ It is rarely a waste of time to pursue something you &apos;re drawn to , even if you end up quitting .
__bs__ You might apply that knowledge in a different field entirely , in a way that you couldn &apos;t have anticipated .
__bs__ The third multipotentialite superpower is adaptability ; that is , the ability to morph into whatever you need to be in a given situation .
__bs__ Abe Cajudo is sometimes a video director , sometimes a web designer , sometimes a Kickstarter consultant , sometimes a teacher , and sometimes , apparently , James Bond .
__bs__ ( Laughter ) He &apos;s valuable because he does good work .
__bs__ He &apos;s even more valuable because he can take on various roles , depending on his clients &apos; needs .
__bs__ Fast Company magazine identified adaptability as the single most important skill to develop in order to thrive in the 21st century .
__bs__ The economic world is changing so quickly and unpredictably that it is the individuals and organizations that can pivot in order to meet the needs of the market that are really going to thrive .
__bs__ Idea synthesis , rapid learning and adaptability : three skills that multipotentialites are very adept at , and three skills that they might lose if pressured to narrow their focus .
__bs__ As a society , we have a vested interest in encouraging multipotentialites to be themselves .
__bs__ We have a lot of complex , multidimensional problems in the world right now , and we need creative , out-of-the-box thinkers to tackle them .
__bs__ Now , let &apos;s say that you are , in your heart , a specialist .
__bs__ You came out of the womb knowing you wanted to be a pediatric neurosurgeon .
__bs__ Don &apos;t worry — there &apos;s nothing wrong with you , either .
__bs__ ( Laughter ) In fact , some of the best teams are comprised of a specialist and multipotentialite paired together .
__bs__ The specialist can dive in deep and implement ideas , while the multipotentialite brings a breadth of knowledge to the project .
__bs__ It &apos;s a beautiful partnership .
__bs__ But we should all be designing lives and careers that are aligned with how we &apos;re wired .
__bs__ And sadly , multipotentialites are largely being encouraged simply to be more like their specialist peers .
__bs__ So with that said , if there is one thing you take away from this talk , I hope that it is this : embrace your inner wiring , whatever that may be .
__bs__ If you &apos;re a specialist at heart , then by all means , specialize .
__bs__ That is where you &apos;ll do your best work .
__bs__ But to the multipotentialites in the room , including those of you who may have just realized in the last 12 minutes that you are one — ( Laughter ) to you I say : embrace your many passions .
__bs__ Follow your curiosity down those rabbit holes .
__bs__ Explore your intersections .
__bs__ Embracing our inner wiring leads to a happier , more authentic life .
__bs__ And perhaps more importantly — multipotentialites , the world needs us .
