__bs__ I find the last two words under &quot; &quot; Near Antonyms , &quot; &quot; particularly unsettling : &quot; whole &quot; and &quot; wholesome . &quot;
__bs__ So , it &apos;s not just about the words .
__bs__ It &apos;s what we believe about people when we name them with these words .
__bs__ It &apos;s about the values behind the words , and how we construct those values .
__bs__ Our language affects our thinking and how we view the world and how we view other people .
__bs__ In fact , many ancient societies , including the Greeks and the Romans , believed that to utter a curse verbally was so powerful , because to say the thing out loud brought it into existence .
__bs__ So , what reality do we want to call into existence : a person who is limited , or a person who &apos;s empowered ?
__bs__ By casually doing something as simple as naming a person , a child , we might be putting lids and casting shadows on their power .
__bs__ Wouldn &apos;t we want to open doors for them instead ?
__bs__ One such person who opened doors for me was my childhood doctor at the A.I. duPont Institute in Wilmington , Delaware .
__bs__ His name was Dr. Pizzutillo , an Italian American , whose name , apparently , was too difficult for most Americans to pronounce , so he went by Dr. P.
__bs__ And Dr. P always wore really colorful bow ties and had the very perfect disposition to work with children .
__bs__ I loved almost everything about my time spent at this hospital , with the exception of my physical therapy sessions .
__bs__ I had to do what seemed like innumerable repetitions of exercises with these thick , elastic bands — different colors , you know — to help build up my leg muscles , and I hated these bands more than anything — I hated them , had names for them . I hated them .
__bs__ And , you know , I was already bargaining , as a five year-old child , with Dr. P to try to get out of doing these exercises , unsuccessfully , of course .
__bs__ And , one day , he came in to my session — exhaustive and unforgiving , these sessions — and he said to me , &quot; &quot; Wow . Aimee , you are such a strong and powerful little girl , I think you &apos;re going to break one of those bands .
__bs__ When you do break it , I &apos;m going to give you a hundred bucks . &quot; &quot; Now , of course , this was a simple ploy on Dr. P &apos;s part to get me to do the exercises I didn &apos;t want to do before the prospect of being the richest five-year-old in the second floor ward , but what he effectively did for me was reshape an awful daily occurrence into a new and promising experience for me .
__bs__ And I have to wonder today to what extent his vision and his declaration of me as a strong and powerful little girl shaped my own view of myself as an inherently strong , powerful and athletic person well into the future .
__bs__ This is an example of how adults in positions of power can ignite the power of a child .
__bs__ But , in the previous instances of those thesaurus entries , our language isn &apos;t allowing us to evolve into the reality that we would all want , the possibility of an individual to see themselves as capable .
__bs__ Our language hasn &apos;t caught up with the changes in our society , many of which have been brought about by technology .
__bs__ Certainly , from a medical standpoint , my legs , laser surgery for vision impairment , titanium knees and hip replacements for aging bodies that are allowing people to more fully engage with their abilities , and move beyond the limits that nature has imposed on them — not to mention social networking platforms allow people to self-identify , to claim their own descriptions of themselves , so they can go align with global groups of their own choosing .
__bs__ So , perhaps technology is revealing more clearly to us now what has always been a truth : that everyone has something rare and powerful to offer our society , and that the human ability to adapt is our greatest asset .
__bs__ The human ability to adapt , it &apos;s an interesting thing , because people have continually wanted to talk to me about overcoming adversity , and I &apos;m going to make an admission : This phrase never sat right with me , and I always felt uneasy trying to answer people &apos;s questions about it , and I think I &apos;m starting to figure out why .
__bs__ Implicit in this phrase of &quot; &quot; overcoming adversity &quot; &quot; is the idea that success , or happiness , is about emerging on the other side of a challenging experience unscathed or unmarked by the experience , as if my successes in life have come about from an ability to sidestep or circumnavigate the presumed pitfalls of a life with prosthetics , or what other people perceive as my disability .
__bs__ But , in fact , we are changed . We are marked , of course , by a challenge , whether physically , emotionally or both .
__bs__ And I &apos;m going to suggest that this is a good thing .
__bs__ Adversity isn &apos;t an obstacle that we need to get around in order to resume living our life .
__bs__ It &apos;s part of our life .
__bs__ And I tend to think of it like my shadow .
__bs__ Sometimes I see a lot of it , sometimes there &apos;s very little , but it &apos;s always with me .
__bs__ And , certainly , I &apos;m not trying to diminish the impact , the weight , of a person &apos;s struggle .
__bs__ There is adversity and challenge in life , and it &apos;s all very real and relative to every single person , but the question isn &apos;t whether or not you &apos;re going to meet adversity , but how you &apos;re going to meet it .
__bs__ So , our responsibility is not simply shielding those we care for from adversity , but preparing them to meet it well .
__bs__ And we do a disservice to our kids when we make them feel that they &apos;re not equipped to adapt .
__bs__ There &apos;s an important difference and distinction between the objective medical fact of my being an amputee and the subjective societal opinion of whether or not I &apos;m disabled .
__bs__ And , truthfully , the only real and consistent disability I &apos;ve had to confront is the world ever thinking that I could be described by those definitions .
__bs__ In our desire to protect those we care about by giving them the cold , hard truth about their medical prognosis , or , indeed , a prognosis on the expected quality of their life , we have to make sure that we don &apos;t put the first brick in a wall that will actually disable someone .
__bs__ Perhaps the existing model of only looking at what is broken in you and how do we fix it , serves to be more disabling to the individual than the pathology itself .
__bs__ By not treating the wholeness of a person , by not acknowledging their potency , we are creating another ill on top of whatever natural struggle they might have .
__bs__ We are effectively grading someone &apos;s worth to our community .
__bs__ So we need to see through the pathology and into the range of human capability .
__bs__ And , most importantly , there &apos;s a partnership between those perceived deficiencies and our greatest creative ability .
__bs__ So it &apos;s not about devaluing , or negating , these more trying times as something we want to avoid or sweep under the rug , but instead to find those opportunities wrapped in the adversity .
__bs__ So maybe the idea I want to put out there is not so much overcoming adversity as it is opening ourselves up to it , embracing it , grappling with it , to use a wrestling term , maybe even dancing with it .
__bs__ And , perhaps , if we see adversity as natural , consistent and useful , we &apos;re less burdened by the presence of it .
__bs__ This year we celebrate the 200th birthday of Charles Darwin , and it was 150 years ago , when writing about evolution , that Darwin illustrated , I think , a truth about the human character .
